SIMPLE: imitate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Imitate
<hw>Im"i*tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Imitated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Imitating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>imitatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>imitari</ets> to imitate; of unknown
origin. Cf. <er>Image</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To follow as a
pattern, model, or example; to copy or strive to copy, in acts, manners
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Despise wealth and <qex>imitate</qex> a dog.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowlay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To produce a semblance or likeness of, in form,
character, color, qualities, conduct, manners, and the like; to
counterfeit; to copy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A place picked out by choice of best alive⟦br⟧
The Nature's work by art can <qex>imitate</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This hand appeared a shining sword to weild,⟦br⟧
And that sustained an <qex>imitated</qex> shield.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>To resemble (another species of
animal, or a plant, or inanimate object) in form, color, ornamentation,
or instinctive habits, so as to derive an advantage thereby; as, when a
harmless snake <xex>imitates</xex> a venomous one in color and manner,
or when an odorless insect <xex>imitates</xex>, in color, one having
secretion offensive to birds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Imitation</ent>⟦br⟧
